%%TITLE
Increasing rates of low-risk human papillomavirus infections in patients with oral cavity squamous cell carcinoma: association with clinical outcomes.
%%ABSTRACT
Although human papillomavirus (HPV) infections have been causally linked to oral cavity squamous cell carcinoma (OSCC), the potential role of low-risk HPV (LR-HPV) types in the pathogenesis of this malignancy remains unclear.We sought to investigate the distribution of HPV genotypes and their prognostic significance in OSCC patients treated by radical surgery, either with or without adjuvant therapy.We studied two non-overlapping OSCC cohorts for the periods 2005-2006 (2005 cohort, n = 204) and 2010-2011 (2010 cohort, n = 206). Paraffin-embedded tissue blocks were collected, and the HPV genotype was determined using PCR plus HPV blot tests. The primary study endpoint was the prevalence of HPV genotypes. The secondary endpoints were the 2-year therapeutic outcomes.The overall prevalence of HPV infections did not differ significantly in the two study cohorts. However, the prevalence of LR-HPV was significantly higher in the 2010 cohort than in the 2005 cohort (p = 0.002). The overall prevalence of HPV infections was not significantly associated with the 2-year outcomes. However, multivariate analysis demonstrated that LR-HPV infection was a predictor of poor 2-year disease-free survival (p = 0.036, hazard ratio [HR] = 3.1), disease-specific survival (p = 0.014, HR = 3.8), and overall survival (p = 0.016, HR = 3.2) in the subgroups of OSCC patients with poor differentiation, pN2 lymph node metastases, or extracapsular spread (n = 150).LR-HPV infections may have an important role in determining the clinical outcomes of certain OSCC patients bearing specific risk factors.
%%METHODS
Study population and design
This study was designed as a single-center, retrospective case series aimed at investigating the molecular prevalence of HPV infections among Taiwanese OSCC patients referred to the Chang Gung Memorial Hospital, Linkou Medical Center, Taoyuan, Taiwan. The investigation was powered to detect prevalence rates as low as 0% in a reliable manner. We calculated that the absence of HPV infections among 400 OSCC patients would generate a one-sided 97.5% conﬁdence interval (CI) between 0% and 0.92%.
Only formalin-ﬁxed, parafﬁn-embedded (FFPE) specimens from patients with newly diagnosed OSCC were included in this study. All of the OSCC patients were treated with radical surgery with curative intent. Two distinct cohorts were enrolled in this study (2005 cohort, n = 204; 2010 cohort, n = 206). The inclusion criteria were as follows: (a) pathologically proven OSCC, (b) presence of a previously untreated tumor scheduled for radical surgery with or without neck dissection, and (c) absence of suspected distant metastases on imaging. Patients who refused to participate or did not undergo radical surgery were excluded. The traditional risk fac- tors for OSCC were extracted from clinical records and classiﬁed as described previously. The following variables were collected: sex, age, alcohol drinking, betel quid chewing, cigarette smok- ing, tumor location, histological differentiation, pathological tumor status, pathological lymph node status, pathological stage, extra- capsular spread, and treatment modality. The tumor location was determined by direct oral inspection and conﬁrmed by pathologi- cal examination. OSCC patients were staged according to the 2002 American Joint Committee on Cancer 6th edition staging criteria. Postoperative radiotherapy or concomitant chemoradiation ther- apy were used for adjuvant treatment of patients with advanced OSCC. The classiﬁcation of therapeutic outcomes has been previ- ously described. The Institutional Review Board approved the study protocol, and written informed consent was obtained from all participants.
DNA extraction and MY11/GP6+ polymerase chain reaction (PCR)
Primary tumors were excised with safety margins larger than 1 cm (all peripheral and deep margins). The FFPE tumor tissues were prepared for DNA extraction as previously described.µL of the 50 µL eluted DNA solution was used as the PCR template. An HPV L1 gene PCR assay was used to screen for HPV infections. HPV DNA was ampliﬁed using MY11/biotinylated GP6+ primers target- ing the L1 region, which produced a 192-bp DNA fragment. DNA quality was assessed in each run using a �-globin PCR. All of the obtained specimens were found to be �-globin-positive.
HPV genotyping by Eastchip® HPV blot
Specimens were further tested for the presence of HPV and its genotypes by amplifying 50 µL of the DNA extracts using the EasyChip® HPV Blot genotyping assay (King Car Ltd, Ilan, Taiwan). HPV type-speciﬁc oligonucleotide probes were immobilized on a nylon membrane for reverse-blot hybridization to detect HPV DNA in a single assay.Two independent PCR products of each sam- ple were hybridized with an HPV blot, and the two HPV blot results were compared with each other. The HPV blot kit enabled the dif- ferential detection of 39 HPV types (i.e., HPV types 6, 11, 16, 18, 26, 31–33, 35, 37, 39, 42–45, 51–56, 58, 59, 61, 62, 66–70, 71 [CP8061],
72, 74, 81 [CP8304], 82 [MM4], 83 [MM7], 84 [MM8], and L1AE5).
The high-risk HPV types included types 16, 18, 31, 33, 35, 39, 45, 51, 52, 56, 58, 59, and 68, whereas HPV types 6, 11, 26, 32, 37, 42–44,
53–55, 61, 62, 66, 67, 69–72, 74, 81–84, and L1AE5 were classi-
ﬁed as low-risk types. HR-HPV positivity was deﬁned as having at least one of the 13 high-risk types. Patients with both high-risk and low-risk HPV types were classiﬁed as having HR-HPV infec- tions. LR-HPV positivity was deﬁned by the presence of single or multiple infections by low-risk HPV genotypes only.
Statistical analysis
The overall prevalence of the HPV genotypes was calculated, and the distribution of speciﬁc HPV genotypes was expressed as the proportion of HPV DNA-positive specimens among all of the

Categorical variables were analyzed using the chi-square test or the Fisher’s exact test, as appropriate. Follow-up visits continued until December 2012. The 2-year local control, neck control, dis- tant metastasis, DFS, DSS, and OS rates were calculated using the Kaplan–Meier method (log-rank test). Multivariate Cox regression analysis with a backward selection procedure was used to identify the independent prognostic factors. The results were expressed as hazard ratios (HR) and 95% CI. We calculated the study power for the survival analysis using the R software (Version 2.15.3; R Foundation for Statistical Computing, ). Other calcu- lations were performed using the SPSS software (version 17.0; SPSS, Inc., Chicago, IL, USA). Two-tailed p values < 0.05 were considered statistically signiﬁcant.
